context, Lizbet Simmons shows how young black males are in the liminal state of losing educational affiliation while being caught in the net of correctional control. In The Prison School, she asks how schools and prisons became so intertwined. What does this mean for students, communities, and a democratic society? And how do we unravel the ties that bind the racialized realities of school failure and mass incarceration?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican American young menxDisciplinexLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aAfrican American young menxEducationxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aJuvenile correctionsxLouisianaxNew Orleans. 0aSchool disciplinexLouisianaxNew Orleans. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066754740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520293144?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520293144423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520293144/original  a978-3-11-066754-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles